Prince Charles helps raise funds for Clutha TrustPRINCE Charles signed a ukulele to help raise funds for the Clutha Trust on a visit to the tragic bar where ten people were killed.The Duke of Rothesay visited the Stockwell Street pub in November 2013 just days after a police helicopter plunged into the roof killing the pilot and two police officers on board as well seven people inside.He spoke to survivors and emergency workers and and signed the book of condolence.But on a return visit with his wife Camilla yesterday Prince Charles spent time with the Clutha Trust, a charity working to support young people in the aftermath of the crash.The royal couple signed a ukulele which will now be auctioned to raise funds for the trust.When he arrived, Prince Charles was greeted by Clutha owner Alan Crossan and stopped to admire a mural of well-known faces painted on the outside of the Stockwell Street bar.The Royal couple passed through the Clutha, which has been closed since the night of the tragedy, to the bar's garden area where they also met representatives from the Prince's Trust, the Gorbals Barn Project and Royston Youth Action.Charles signed and dated the special instrument before enjoying a drink in the adjoining Victoria bar and listening to musicians from the Prince's Trust perform.